<refsect1 lang = "en"><title>&desc-tt;</title>
<para><filename>security_drivers</filename> lists the collection of drivers used by the Solaris Security Toolkit found in the security.drivers file.</para></refsect1>
<refsect1 lang = "en"><title>EXTENDED &desc-tt;</title>
<para>The following list describes briefly the standard drivers:<itemizedlist
    mark = "bullet" spacing = "normal"><listitem><para><filename>config.driver</filename> implements tasks associated with the driver set.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><filename>hardening.driver</filename> contains most of the security specific scripts.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><filename>secure.driver</filename> is the default driver used in the rules for client installation. Implements all the hardening functionality. </para></listitem>
<listitem><para><filename>server-secure.driver</filename> is based on the secure.driver, and highlights what might be necessary to secure server systems. </para></listitem>
<listitem><para><filename>suncluster3x-secure.driver</filename> provides a baseline configuration for hardening Sun&trade; Cluster 3.x software releases. </para></listitem>
<listitem><para><filename>sunfire_15k_sc-secure.driver</filename> is the only supported mechanism by which the Sun Fire high-end system controller can be secured. </para></listitem></itemizedlist></para>
<para>For detailed information and instructions on the use of each of these drivers please refer to the Chapter 4, &ldquo;Drivers&rdquo;, in the <citetitle pubwork = "book">&SST-REFMAN;</citetitle>.</para></refsect1>
<refsect1 lang = "en"><title>&exam-tt;</title>
<example width = "100" os = "solaris"><title>Contents of the <filename>secure.driver File</filename></title><screen width = "100" format = "linespecific">
DIR="`/bin/dirname $0`"
export DIR

. ${DIR}/driver.init

. ${DIR}/config.driver

. ${DIR}/hardening.driver
</screen></example></refsect1>
